<div id="review_4049301771" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4049301771" />
    <a title="Cédric" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58423772-c-dric"><img alt="Cédric" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1470561675p2/58423772.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4049301771?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cédric" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cédric" href="/user/show/58423772-c-dric">Cédric</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4049301771" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13328044642595836523">Bari Wood’s 1982 occult suspense thriller opens in Nuremberg at the end of WWII, where a Nazi criminal reveals why the inmates of Belzec Extermination Camp’s hut 554 were all found alive while the abject horror of mass murder on industrial scale was taking place all around and why traces of a curious clay-like substance was coating the floor of the said hut and the clothes of its occupants. Fast forward to New York in 1981, where Adam Levy, a Jewish university teacher, is mugged and murdered by </span>
  <span id="freeText13328044642595836523" style="display:none">Bari Wood’s 1982 occult suspense thriller opens in Nuremberg at the end of WWII, where a Nazi criminal reveals why the inmates of Belzec Extermination Camp’s hut 554 were all found alive while the abject horror of mass murder on industrial scale was taking place all around and why traces of a curious clay-like substance was coating the floor of the said hut and the clothes of its occupants. Fast forward to New York in 1981, where Adam Levy, a Jewish university teacher, is mugged and murdered by a teenage gang. Later on, the perpetrators are all found dismembered in the basement of a tenement in Brooklyn, covered with mud resembling clay. Roger Hawkins, an African American inspector and best friend of the murdered man is leading an investigation which will lead him to the most extreme end of Jewish mythology. <br /><br />Upon reading this powerful novel, it is abundantly clear that Bari Wood is aware of how potentially ridiculous her ‘monster’ might be. So, just like the most adroit of B-horror movie directors, the writer keeps it in the shadows until she has no other choice but to reveal it. But by the time this happens, namely at the ending, it no longer matters whether it works or not, because the supernatural element of the novel has become merely the thread on which the true novel has blossomed. <i>The Tribe</i> offers many moments of thoughtful introspection through its numerous flashbacks, artfully interwoven with the main story line, giving us real and complex characters, with their qualities, faults, prejudices and candour. This allows Bari Wood to confront difficult and potentially hazardous themes such as the uneasy relationship Judaism, which is minutely, fascinatingly and lovingly described, has with women or racial fear, tension and intolerance. She bravely examines these themes with honesty and without ever taking any political stance. Like most great writer, Bari Wood shows complete confidence in her readership and dares to leave any conclusion - if there’s any to draw - to us. A brilliant, well written and finely crafted book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13328044642595836523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

