<div id="review_2903199677" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2903199677" />
    <a title="Scotty" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6524277-scotty"><img alt="Scotty" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577607088p2/6524277.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2903199677?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scotty" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scotty" href="/user/show/6524277-scotty">Scotty</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/45141870-the-tribe">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2903199677" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15667016612704113424">I’ve read a few of Bari Wood’s books before (Twins, Doll’s Eyes, and The Basement) but somehow I never got around to reading The Tribe. I don’t remember The Basement all that well, but I do know I enjoyed it. Twins was great, and the drab realism makes it much creepier than the more baroque Cronenberg adaptation (which I also love). As much as I liked it, though, I’m not sure I’d ever read it again. It’s a profoundly upsetting book precisely because it’s so realistic. Doll’s Eyes is quite a bit </span>
  <span id="freeText15667016612704113424" style="display:none">I’ve read a few of Bari Wood’s books before (Twins, Doll’s Eyes, and The Basement) but somehow I never got around to reading The Tribe. I don’t remember The Basement all that well, but I do know I enjoyed it. Twins was great, and the drab realism makes it much creepier than the more baroque Cronenberg adaptation (which I also love). As much as I liked it, though, I’m not sure I’d ever read it again. It’s a profoundly upsetting book precisely because it’s so realistic. Doll’s Eyes is quite a bit pulpier, which makes it a lot more entertaining. <br /><br />The Tribe might be Wood’s masterpiece (it’s a toss-up between it and Doll’s Eyes for me). It’s the best of both worlds; it takes the kitchen-sink New York realism of Twins and marries it to a classic monster story. It’s also deeply humane, using a central figure from Jewish folklore to explore the rage and continuing trauma inflicted by the Holocaust. I’m Jewish myself, but my family is non-practicing and I’ve always felt fairly disconnected from that heritage. The Tribe mines into that disconnection and emotionally connected me to my family’s history in a way I didn’t expect. <br /><br />There’s a lot going on here — monsters, murders, racism, faith — so I guess it’s inevitable that the ending would be a bit of an anti-climax. As much as I admire Wood for largely eschewing genre tropes, she didn’t quite deliver the goods. <br /><br />Still, this is a classic, and it proves once again that Wood is one of horror’s most underrated practitioners. Doll’s Eyes is still my favorite, but The Tribe is arguably the better book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15667016612704113424" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

