<div id="review_3055790277" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3055790277" />
    <a title="James Cannon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60890039-james-cannon"><img alt="James Cannon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624966076p2/60890039.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3055790277?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James Cannon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James Cannon" href="/user/show/60890039-james-cannon">James Cannon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60890039-james-cannon?shelf=dnf">dnf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3055790277" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10943476420136055578">The book has an intriguing premise and a promising first chapter, but it ends up being simply melodramatic and silly. There are far too many characters. And the main character Hawkins feels like a example of reverse racism, since he&apos;s so perfect he might as well be wearing a cape (no wonder Stephen King offered the book a gushing review.) Finally, and this is a criticism that can only be leveled against books that promise horror, this book isn&apos;t scary in the least. There&apos;s no suspense, no dread.</span>
  <span id="freeText10943476420136055578" style="display:none">The book has an intriguing premise and a promising first chapter, but it ends up being simply melodramatic and silly. There are far too many characters. And the main character Hawkins feels like a example of reverse racism, since he's so perfect he might as well be wearing a cape (no wonder Stephen King offered the book a gushing review.) Finally, and this is a criticism that can only be leveled against books that promise horror, this book isn't scary in the least. There's no suspense, no dread. <br /><br />The book is also full of clumsy scenes like this one: <br /><br /><blockquote>Hawkins groaned again and someone touched his shoulder. <br />"You okay, man?"<br />A huge black man squatted next to him...<br />"You sick, man?" he asked....<br />"Hey, boy," the black man said, rubbing Hawkin's back gently. "Nothin' kin be so bad. I'll git you a drink, a steak, find you a little nookie, you'll be okay, boy."<br />"I'm okay," Hawkins said.<br />"No, you ain't. You in awful condition...what happened to you?"<br />Hawkins looked at the other man's gentle homely face and said, "A man I love is a murderer and I can make him pay for it - " he stopped. <br />"A man?" he said. "A lover man, a frien', what?"<br />"Like...a father," Hawkins answered.<br />The man stopped brushing and looked very serious. <br />"You can't bitch aroun' with yo' daddy, boy, no matter what he done."</blockquote><br /><br />Never mind the cringe-inducing dialogue, who is this random guy who's offering him this wisdom and what's his motivation? This was the scene that broke the book's back.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10943476420136055578" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


