<div id="review_3020935133" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3020935133" />
    <a title="Genevieve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9007607-genevieve"><img alt="Genevieve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1375979963p2/9007607.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3020935133?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Genevieve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Genevieve" href="/user/show/9007607-genevieve">Genevieve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781948405324" href="/book/show/45141871-the-tribe">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9007607-genevieve?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9007607-genevieve?shelf=women-authors">women-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9007607-genevieve?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3020935133" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7361915414493954433">What can I say about this unique horror novel. First of all, I was intrigued to read a horror novel that is based in Judaism and the use of a Golem. But this book is so much more than a scary book about a faceless monster sent out to do its master&apos;s bidding. It&apos;s a book about the trauma of the holocaust, the insellar nature of some Jewish communities and the extreme othering of those who aren&apos;t Jewish. A gritty 80&apos;s novel sent in NYC and its outer lying areas that deals with the friendship betwe</span>
  <span id="freeText7361915414493954433" style="display:none">What can I say about this unique horror novel. First of all, I was intrigued to read a horror novel that is based in Judaism and the use of a Golem. But this book is so much more than a scary book about a faceless monster sent out to do its master's bidding. It's a book about the trauma of the holocaust, the insellar nature of some Jewish communities and the extreme othering of those who aren't Jewish. A gritty 80's novel sent in NYC and its outer lying areas that deals with the friendship between a Jewish Rabbi, Jacob Levy, and a Black Detective, Roger Hawkins, that soon goes off the rails after the murder of the rabbi's son. There's racial tension and racial/homophobic/sexist language used in this book that is specific to 1981 but it doesn't feel gratuitous or done without thought. Bari Wood's writing flows beautifully and every word feels purposeful. There's so much more happening in this book than just murder. There's the interaction between White and Black people, the interaction between Men and Women and particularly poignant the relationship between Jewish men and Jewish women that's handled in such a wonderfully fraught way. Overall a truly fascinating gem of an early horror novel that is thought provoking. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7361915414493954433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


