<div id="review_4061029824" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4061029824" />
    <a title="Ryan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/119733-ryan"><img alt="Ryan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1343288512p2/119733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4061029824?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ryan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ryan" href="/user/show/119733-ryan">Ryan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119733-ryan?shelf=recommended">recommended</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4061029824" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12224017749431531323">So the reason I didn&apos;t rate this too high was not because I thought it was mediocre. Actually it&apos;s really good and deserves a higher rating. But the rating is subjective and really for me. By that I mean I was expecting a horror story instead of a very well written story about culture and belonging in early 80&apos;s New York. There are some horror elements, but nothing meant to be scary. <br/><br/>The golem is a horror trope that has not been explored as thoroughly as say vampires and werewolves. There is som</span>
  <span id="freeText12224017749431531323" style="display:none">So the reason I didn't rate this too high was not because I thought it was mediocre. Actually it's really good and deserves a higher rating. But the rating is subjective and really for me. By that I mean I was expecting a horror story instead of a very well written story about culture and belonging in early 80's New York. There are some horror elements, but nothing meant to be scary. <br /><br />The golem is a horror trope that has not been explored as thoroughly as say vampires and werewolves. There is some really great potential there. And the idea of a man made out of clay that is controlled by Rabbis and can tear people apart is really a scary idea, but not employed as anything more than a plot device here. The entire thing is grounded in the Holocaust. And for my money, it would have been a genuine pulp horror story if it all took place then. The story does mention how the Nazis were killing Jews, but were afraid to touch a small group of men. Those men chose to ignore the fate of thousands to keep themselves alive. Had that been the entire plot, this would have been more exciting and dark. Like I said, it's not really fair to judge a story based on my expectations. OK.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12224017749431531323" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


