<div id="review_2903137448" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2903137448" />
    <a title="Hayley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/92120733-hayley"><img alt="Hayley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547435264p2/92120733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2903137448?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hayley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hayley" href="/user/show/92120733-hayley">Hayley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2903137448" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5056407702980785439">This is the first book from the Paperbacks from Hell re-releases that I&apos;ve read, and I loved it! I went in for the monster story (of which, there is actually not a whole lot of focus) and stayed for the wonderful characters and great settings. I particularly love Rachel Levy as a character - she is fierce and strong in the face of adversity and her struggles with identity. <br/><br/>The thing I probably loved the most about this book was the pieces about Judaism, about which I know very little. Characters</span>
  <span id="freeText5056407702980785439" style="display:none">This is the first book from the Paperbacks from Hell re-releases that I've read, and I loved it! I went in for the monster story (of which, there is actually not a whole lot of focus) and stayed for the wonderful characters and great settings. I particularly love Rachel Levy as a character - she is fierce and strong in the face of adversity and her struggles with identity. <br /><br />The thing I probably loved the most about this book was the pieces about Judaism, about which I know very little. Characters like Rachel, Chaim, and Golda really came alive for me, and I felt that the book really conveyed what it is like to be Jewish in New York in the late 70s. The racial tensions between the Jewish characters and the African American characters is also interesting - again, as a white Protestant girl who grew up in the 90s, this is new territory for me. The book also poses the question of what it is to be Jewish in the aftermath of the Holocaust, and if there ever truly is healing from so horrible a genocide. <br /><br />5 stars from me, and I can't wait to read more of these re-releases!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5056407702980785439" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


