<span id="freeTextContainer9227126396305093080">The Paperbacks from Hell reprints continue to surprise for both the breadth of novels as well as the quality of those same novels. This is the fifth of the reprints I&apos;ve read and only one of them wasn&apos;t really to my liking. Bari Wood&apos;s The Tribe might be the best of the first batch of reprints.<br/><br/>A story divided into 4 parts where the focus moves from protagonist to protagonist it&apos;s essentially telling the story of two people. A black police inspector, Hawkins, who is kind of adopted by an avuncula</span>
  <span id="freeText9227126396305093080" style="display:none">The Paperbacks from Hell reprints continue to surprise for both the breadth of novels as well as the quality of those same novels. This is the fifth of the reprints I've read and only one of them wasn't really to my liking. Bari Wood's The Tribe might be the best of the first batch of reprints.<br /><br />A story divided into 4 parts where the focus moves from protagonist to protagonist it's essentially telling the story of two people. A black police inspector, Hawkins, who is kind of adopted by an avuncular Rabbi, Jacob Levy, in a difficult period of his life; and Rachel Levy, Jacob's daughter-in-law and widow of his son, Hawkin's best friend. <br /><br />The rabbi and his coterie are a group of Holocaust survivors who as a survival mechanism created a Golem in the old country to keep the nazis off their backs at the concentration camp, but when the war is over they bring their knowledge to the US where a mix of trauma and justified paranoia will lead to disastrous consequences. A book on race relations, survivor's guilt, trauma, and a big clay monster.</span>
