<div id="review_2933522552" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2933522552" />
    <a title="Richard Schaefer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69345290-richard-schaefer"><img alt="Richard Schaefer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560284325p2/69345290.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2933522552?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard Schaefer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard Schaefer" href="/user/show/69345290-richard-schaefer">Richard Schaefer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781948405324" href="/book/show/45141871-the-tribe">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2933522552" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2834167039698665178">I really wanted to like The Tribe, Bari Wood’s 1981 horror novel. It promised discussion of class and race, a mystery, mysticism, and, duh, horror. Unfortunately, it didn’t deliver on any of those promises to this reader: the subject of class and race permeate the book, but I often wondered why this particular writer felt the need to take them on; there was no mystery to the book, it made sure to dispense with that early on (retaining only the tone of a mainstream mystery of the era); some of th</span>
  <span id="freeText2834167039698665178" style="display:none">I really wanted to like The Tribe, Bari Wood’s 1981 horror novel. It promised discussion of class and race, a mystery, mysticism, and, duh, horror. Unfortunately, it didn’t deliver on any of those promises to this reader: the subject of class and race permeate the book, but I often wondered why this particular writer felt the need to take them on; there was no mystery to the book, it made sure to dispense with that early on (retaining only the tone of a mainstream mystery of the era); some of the mysticism was compelling, but hardly revolutionary to anyone familiar with the golem legend; and the horror, oh the lack of horror! The book is not scary, and I have to think that the publisher deemed it “horror” for lack of a better category for a novel that includes a gigantic clay man who tears people apart at the whim of its controller(s).<br /><br />See my full review (mild spoilers) in my blog:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://richardcharlesschaefer.wordpress.com/2019/09/04/a-handful-of-clay-on-bari-woods-the-tribe/">https://richardcharlesschaefer.wordpr...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="2834167039698665178" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


